Exercise 2

The data set used for this exercise consists of data gathered from a survey on a course, where 183 students answered it. The survey asked from the students about their attitudes towards learning and studying. They were asked deep, surface and strategic level questions. The data set used in this exercise is a modified version of this data where students who got 0 exam points have been excluded leaving 166 students. Their attitudes and question scores have been averaged to reflect the original scaling of the questions. Overall the data set has 166 observations from the students and 7 variables consisting of the gender of the student, age of the student, attitude, three different question types and exam points. Most of the data consists of numeric data except for the gender variable which is character type data.

Basic information about the data:

Commentary on the data:

In the data set there are a total of 166 students, out of these 110 (66%) are female while 56 (34%) are male. According to the summary of the variables the average age of a student in the course was 25, but the students ranged in age from 17 to 55, but with most students being under the age of 27. In their attitudes the students varied between unmotivated (1.4) and very motivated (5). In the case of attitude it’s median (3.2) and mean (3.1) are close to each other and reflect average to good motivation. For the different question types the strategic questions have a similar distribution as the attitude variable, but deep questions have higher values and surface questions lower overall. The lowest points in the exam were 7, while highest were 33, the average being 22.7.

Regression analysis:

I chose attitude, strategic questions and surface questions as my explanatory variables in the model as they had the highest correlation with exam points.

lm_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learn14)

## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08

The statistical test used in the model assumes the null hypothesis that an explanatory variable has no effect on the target variable. The t value represents the estimate of an explanatory variable divided by its standard error. A small standard error will result in higher t value. The p value represents the likelihood of obtaining this t value if the null hypothesis is true, small p value means that it is very unlikely that we can get the observed data distribution by chance.

According to the summary ‘attitude’ would have the highest effect on the target variable as its estimate is ~3.4 and would affect the slope of the model quite a bit. On the other hand ‘stra’ and ‘surf’ are 0.85 and -0.58 respectively and would have little effect on the tatget variable as their effect on the slope would be near zero.

Out of the three explanatory variables ‘attitude’ is the only one that has an interesting estimated value with also a correspondingly high t value and statistically significant p value. ‘stra’ and ‘surf’ on the other hand did not have statistically significant relationship with the target value as their p values were too high.

The strategic and surface level questions did not have statistically significant p values so I removed them from the next model.

library(ggplot2)

## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

The significance of attitude increased and the p value is even smaller after removing the other two variables. The effect on the slope of the model also increased as the estimate for ‘attitude’ increased to 3.5.

Multiple R-squared represents how much of the target variable can be explained by the explanatory variables, the higher the value the better the model is generally considered to be. In this case the model with only attitude variable can explain around 19% of the variance seen in the points variable.

par(mfrow =c(2,2))
plot(lm_model, which = c(1,2,5))

In linear regression we assume that the relationship between the target value and explanatory variables is linear, which we can see in the points ~ attitude plot where the regression lines are clearly diagonal.

General assumptions about the errors in the model are that they are normally distributed, are not correlated and have constant variance. If for example variance is not constant we can see that the residues would disperse in the plots. Errors are also not dependent on any of the variables in the model.

Normality can be observed in the QQ plot where if the residues are normally distributed they will mostly fall on the diagonal line. In my opinion normality holds in this case as most of the points are on the diagonal line and none of them look like they are very far from it if they are not on it.

In the residuals vs fitted plot we can see that there is no pattern or dispersion of the points meaning that the variance of the errors is constant as expected.

There are also not any significant outliers as the Cook’s distance is small for all data points as can be observed in the leverage plot.

Week 3, logistic regression

Exercise 3

The data in this exercise consists of student questionnaire that measured student performance in mathematics and Portuguese language. The questionnaires were performed in two Portuguese high schools in 2008. The data set includes background information about the students’ families, use of time such as study and free time, health information such as a score for overall health and alcohol consumption. Student performance variables include information about the grades and absences. The data includes both categorical data and integer data where lower numbers indicate lower score and higher numbers higher score or satisfaction.

Potentially interesting variables in my opinion are: age, goout, sex, and health.

I think age is an interesting variable as I would expect that older students are more likely to drink or drink heavily in comparison to younger students.

The goout variable refers to going out with friends. As drinking alcohol is often done in social situation such as parties rather than alone I would expect that students who go out a lot with their friends would also drink more. More introverted students would also be less likely to have friends who can acquire alcohol as they likely have less friends overall than more sociable students.

I would also expect to see a sex difference between boys and girls as adult men tend to drink more than women and thus I expect to see this difference already reflected in students. I also expect that boys are overall heavier drinkers than girls as boys are able to metabolize higher quantities of alcohol and are more likely to engage in risky behavior.

The health variable is about the overall health status with low numbers referring to low health and high ones to better health. Excessive drinking could be related to lower overall health.

In the data I have 195 female students and 175 male students. I think this is overall a good distribution and not too biased one way.

The age range of students varies from 15 to 22 with the mean being 16.6. The legal age of drinking wine and beer in Portugal was 16 before a new law introduced in 2015 so most students would have been legally allowed to drink milder alcoholic drinks when the questionnaire was performed but not allowed to drink spirits for which the legal drinking age was 18. A breakdown of students into high and low alcohol users shows that high users are a little older than low users. This is as I expect in my hypothesis. Interestingly girls who are older are less likely to be high alcohol users while older boys are more likely to use alcohol a lot.

The mean value of goout is 3.1 and median 3 so overall students tend to go out not too rarely but not too often either. Like I hypothesized high alcohol users are more likely to go out with their friends. High alcohol user boys are especially likely to go out with their friends while boys who are low alcohol users are the least likely to go out with their friends. Girls who use high quantities of alcohol are also more likely to go out but the comparison to low alcohol using girls is less extreme.

The mean health score is 3.6 so students overall have okay to good health. Interestingly the health of students who are high alcohol users is higher thant that of students who are low users which is not what I expected. Boys who are high alcohol users report the highest health scores while girls who are low alcohol users report the lowest score with girls’ health overall being worse than boys’.

Based on the cross tabulation we can see that the prediction rate for false cases as false is 65.4% and true cases as true 13.2%. The false positive rate is 4.6% and false negative is 16.8%. The model thus overall seems to do worse when predicting who is a high alcohol user and is more likely to predict high alcohol users as low alcohol users than low alcohol users as high alcohol users.

plyr::count(student_data$high_use == student_data$predicted_value)
##       x freq
## 1 FALSE   79
## 2  TRUE  291
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = student_data$high_use, prob = student_data$predicted_value)
## [1] 0.2135135

I have a total of 79 incorrectly predicted individuals and the overall training error rate is 21%. This is not very good when predicting if a student is a heavy alcohol user as the model predicts every fifth student wrong and ideally our model would be basically never wrong if we wanted accurate predictions.

student_data$guess <- sample(c(TRUE, FALSE),370, TRUE, c(0.5,0.5))

plyr::count(student_data$guess)
##       x freq
## 1 FALSE  178
## 2  TRUE  192
loss_func(class = student_data$high_use, prob = student_data$guess)
## [1] 0.5162162

If we guess with a 50% chance of each student being a high alcohol user we get are wrong approximately half the time as the error rate is around 50%. Based on this the model is better than mere random guessing and is at least mildly useful in predicting who is a high alcohol user among the students.

Simple 10-fold cross validation:

library(boot)
cv10 <- cv.glm(data = student_data, cost = loss_func, glmfit = model2, K = 10)

cv10$delta[1]
## [1] 0.227027

According to the 10-fold cross validation the error rate varies around 22%-24% which is better than the datacamp model where the error rate is 26%. Accordingly my model is a tiny bit better than the datacamp model.

My overall conclusion of this exercise is that my hypothesis regarding the student age and health showing a connection between high alcohol use was wrong. These variables did not have a statistically significant relationship between alcohol consumption. On the other hand my hypothesis regarding male students and outgoing students being more likely to be high alcohol users were correct. Additionally I managed to make a model that was slightly better than the datacamp one.

Based on the plots most of the columns do not seem to follow the normal distribution and instead we can see multiple peaks in the data. There seems to be strong negative correlations between ‘dis’ and ‘indus’ (non-retail business) , ‘nox’ (nitrogen oxides) , and ‘age’ (built prior to 1940). A very strong correlation can also be seen between ‘lstat’ (lower status population) and ‘medv’ (median value of homes). It is not particularly surprising that lower status population could afford only cheaper homes.

A strong positive correlation seems to exits between ‘rad’ (access to radial highways) and ‘tax’ (property tax) as well as ‘indus’ and ‘nox’ and between ‘nox’ and ‘age’. It is again not that surprising that areas with more industry would have higher nitrogen oxide levels.

In the summary we can see that crime rates vary from very low with a minimum of 0.006 to very high with a crime rate of 88.98. The median is closer to the low rate so this very high rate is clearly some kind of anomaly within Boston and not reflective of the entire city.

The age variable indicates that there are areas in Boston where almost no houses are old and then there are areas where are houses are old. But old houses seem to be common overall as the first quantile is at 45%.

#copied from the datacamp exercise

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crim)

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes) 
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

The high crime rate and some medium high crime rate datapoints seem to form their own cluster. ‘rad’ (accessibility to radial highways) seems to be the feature that separates this cluster from the others. In the previous correlation plots we can see that there is indeed a positive correaltion between crime rate and ‘rad’.

‘zn’ and ‘nox’ seem to separate the other axis. In this case it separates out the lower crime areas from the medium high ones. The ‘zn’ (residential lots) and ‘nox’ (nitrogen oxide levels) probably correlate between more quiet residential areas and industrial areas or areas near them.

Clustering with k-means:

data("Boston")
scaled_boston <- scale(Boston)

dist_eu <- dist(scaled_boston)

km <-kmeans(scaled_boston, centers = 4)

pairs(scaled_boston, col = km$cluster)

4 clusters does not seem to be all that great as there is still overlap between the different clusters and as the LDA prediction indicated a lower number of clusters is probably better since there is confusion between the classes.

Investigating how many clusters would be good:

twcss <- sapply(1:10, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:10, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

According to the plot 2 clusters seems to be a good number to try.

km <-kmeans(scaled_boston, centers = 2)
pairs(scaled_boston, col = km$cluster)

Now we can see the clusters much easily. It is probably better in the model to separate the crime rate into a high one and low to medium levels.

In the plots we can see for example in the ‘lstat’ and ‘medv’ a clear separation between the two clusters and it would be easy to draw a straight line between them to separate the to clusters. There are also plots where the two clusters are completely separate from each other.

Week 5, dimensionality reduction

Exercise 5

The data set used in this exercise is about country specific human development index (HDI) and gender inequality index (GII).HDI measures the development of the country and includes measurements such as life expectancy and years of education as well as the GNI. GII measures the inequality between the sexes across different countries. GII contains information regarding the secondary educational attainment of the sexes and labour force participation. Additionally the GII measures the number of female representatives in the parliament. GII also contains information regarding the maternal mortality rate as well as the rate of teen pregnancies and births. Overall both HDI and GII rank countries according to how well they do by the things they measure

The human data set used contains country specific information about the ratio of secondary education attainment between women and men, labour force participation ratio between women and men, expected years of education, life expectancy, maternal mortality, teen birth rates, percentage of female parliament members, and GNI. The dataset has these 8 variables for 155 different countries.

Based on these data it can be said that countries with poor education attainment for women have high teen birth rates and high maternal mortality rates and that these countries are overall poorer than countries that have high educational attainment for women and low maternal mortality rates.

s2_lab <- paste0(names(s2), " (", s2, "%)")

When not standardising data the first component captures 99% of the variance in the data while in the standardised data it is 53%, which is much more reasonable. The variance captured by the components after standardisation is quite different, but not surprising. As seen in the first plot most of the variables do not follow normal distribution while PCA works better if the variables follow a normal distribution as then the components are independent from each other. Doing PCA on non-standardised data can result in unintuitive results.

In the two above plots we can see that in the non-standardised data most of the variance can be explained by the GNI of the country and it seems to explain the vast majority of the first PCA component. It is not surprisign that GNI seems to be the most important factor in this case as it correlated in the corrplot with almost all variables and thus may capture all of the variance explained by these other variables too.

In the standardised biplot we can see that there are two clear components. The first component seems to have been able to separate out the effects of the other variables more clearly rather than just lumping them all under GNI. The first component seems to mostly relate to the living conditions of women as the arrows for teen births and maternal mortality point away from expected education and life expectancy which had a negative correlation with the first two variables mentioned. The second component seems to consist of the two variables that GNI did not correlate with strongly, these would be labour ratio between women and men and the representation of women in the parliament. It seems like this component captures information about the participation of women in the economy and political life while the first component is more about general prospects for women or about general poverty.

Overall it seems that none of the dimensions is particularly good at capturing the variance as the first components hover at around 10%. It seems that the tea type affects the first 3 dimensions with the first dimension having a contribution from green tea while the next two dimensions have black and earl grey tea. Another important factor seems to be how the tea was packaged such as tea bag or unpackaged.

lets plot the results:

plot(mca, invisible=c("ind"), habillage = "quali", graph.type = "classic")

I do not think that there is any very clear factors in this plot but it seems that the packaging of the tea, where the tea was bought from and tea type all generally different from each other. On the other hand people who used unpackaged tea seem to have also bought their tea from tea shops while people who used tea bags had bought their tea from a chain store. Additonally, it seems that women were more likely to drink tea with friends while men were more likely to drink tea alone based on the plot.
